拉莫爾根斯拉","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"英国英格兰賀福爾賀福德","lifeSummary":"当Sir Richard Maunsell于大约1295年出生在英国英格兰武斯特斯爾諾費爾德时，他的父亲Phillip De Maunsell11岁，母亲Dorothy Frye9岁。他于1346年与Lucy Scurlage在英国威尔斯格拉莫爾根高維爾结婚。他们至少是1个儿子和1个女儿的父母。他去世于1361年在英国威尔斯格拉莫爾根高維爾享年67岁。"},"hr":{"Abt 1295–1361":"oko 1295.–1361.","1295–1361":"1295–1361.","1312–Male":"1312–preminuo","1314–Male":"1314–preminuo","1318–Male":"1318–preminuo","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330.–1391","1340–1376":"1340.–1376","1285–Male":"1285–preminuo","1288–Female":"1288–preminula","1330":"1330.","1340":"1340.","1285":"1285","1361":"1361.","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"oko 1295.","1314":"1314","1346":"1346.","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"Abt 1295–1361":"okolo 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Zesnulý","1314–Male":"1314–Zesnulý","1318–Male":"1318–Zesnulý","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Zesnulý","1288–Female":"1288–Zesnulá","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"okolo 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1295–1361":"omkring 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Afdød","1314–Male":"1314–Afdød","1318–Male":"1318–Afdød","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Afdød","1288–Female":"1288–Afdød","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"omkring 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1295–1361":"circa 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Overleden","1314–Male":"1314–Overleden","1318–Male":"1318–Overleden","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Overleden","1288–Female":"1288–Overleden","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"circa 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1295–1361":"about 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Deceased","1314–Male":"1314–Deceased","1318–Male":"1318–Deceased","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1288–Female":"1288–Deceased","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"about 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maunsell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish:  see  Mansell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mansell","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands):","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Old French <i>mansel</i> ‘inhabitant of Le Mans or the surrounding area of Maine’. The place was originally named in Latin <i>(ad) Ceromannos</i>, from the name of the Gaulish tribe living there, the <i>Ceromanni</i>. The name was shortened to <i>Celmans</i> and then became <i>Le Mans</i> as a result of the mistaken identification of the first syllable with the Old French demonstrative adjective.","status name for a particular type of feudal tenant, Anglo-Norman French <i>mansel</i>, one who occupied a <i>manse</i> (from Late Latin <i>mansa</i> ‘dwelling’), a measure of land sufficient to support one family."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Maunsell was born about 1295, in Northfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Phillip De Maunsell, was 11 and his mother, Dorothy Frye, was 9. He married Lucy Scurlage in 1346, in Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1361, in Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"Abt 1295–1361":"umbes 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"umbes 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gower, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Scurlage, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Scurlage, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1295–1361":"noin 1295–1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1312–Male":"1312–Kuollut","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1318–Male":"1318–Kuollut","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1340–1376":"1340–1376","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1288–Female":"1288–Kuollut","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","Abt 1295":"noin 1295","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1376":"1376","1318":"1318","Northfield, Worcester, England":"Northfield, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gower, Glamorganshire